tim kaine [SEP] grand strategy and democracy promotion [SEP] what was tim kaine 's grand strategy ? [SEP] he hired her to be the vocalist in his orchestra , " energy force " . [SEP] what did she do after working for him ? [SEP] jazz trumpeter dizzy gillespie heard her and , in 1979 , invited her to sit in on a set at the monterey jazz festival . [SEP] did she ever win any awards ?

don shula [SEP] legacy [SEP] what legacy did shula leave as a coach ? [SEP] shula set numerous records in his 33 seasons as a head coach . he is the all - time leader in victories with 347 . [SEP] did he hold any other records as a coach ? [SEP] he is first in most games coached ( 526 ) , most consecutive seasons coached ( 33 ) , and super bowl losses ( four , tied with bud grant , dan reeves , and marv levy ) . [SEP] did he receive any awards ?
don shula [SEP] legacy [SEP] what legacy did shula leave as a coach ? [SEP] shula set numerous records in his 33 seasons as a head coach . he is the all - time leader in victories with 347 . [SEP] did he hold any other records as a coach ? [SEP] he is first in most games coached ( 526 ) , most consecutive seasons coached ( 33 ) , and super bowl losses ( four , tied with bud grant , dan reeves , and marv levy ) . [SEP] did he receive any awards ? [SEP] shula is honored at the don shula stadium at john carroll university , and the don shula expressway in miami . maasai people [SEP] influences from the outside world [SEP] what kind of influences from the outside world is the article pertaining to ? [SEP] maintaining a traditional pastoral lifestyle has become increasingly difficult due to outside influences of the modern world . [SEP] has this been a positive thing for them or negative ? [SEP] influence ecologists and policy makers about the harm maasai pastoralists were causing [SEP] what problems are they having ? [SEP] policy makers in 1951 to remove all maasai from the serengeti national park and relegate them to areas in and around the ngorongoro conservation area [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ?
maasai people [SEP] influences from the outside world [SEP] what kind of influences from the outside world is the article pertaining to ? [SEP] maintaining a traditional pastoral lifestyle has become increasingly difficult due to outside influences of the modern world . [SEP] has this been a positive thing for them or negative ? [SEP] influence ecologists and policy makers about the harm maasai pastoralists were causing [SEP] what problems are they having ? [SEP] policy makers in 1951 to remove all maasai from the serengeti national park and relegate them to areas in and around the ngorongoro conservation area [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] increase in maasai population , loss of cattle populations to disease , and lack of available rangelands because of new park boundaries and the incursion of settlements and farms [SEP] what kind of lifestyle do they have ?

joseph mccarthy [SEP] support from roman catholics and the kennedy family [SEP] what support he provide for roman catholics ? [SEP] one of the strongest bases of anti - communist sentiment in the united states was the catholic community , which constituted over 20 % of the national vote . [SEP] what was his involvement with that group ? [SEP] mccarthy identified himself as catholic , and although the great majority of catholics were democrats , as his fame as a leading anti - communist grew , [SEP] what cooperation he had with them ? [SEP] he became popular in catholic communities across the country , with strong support from many leading catholics , diocesan newspapers , and catholic journals . culture of turkey [SEP] prose [SEP] when did prose become important in turkish culture ? [SEP] the style of the current novelists can be traced back to the " young pens " ( genc kalemler ) journal in the ottoman period . [SEP] what was the journal about ? [SEP] young pens was published in selanik under omer seyfettin , ziya gokalp and ali canip yontem . [SEP] were there any other important journals ?
culture of turkey [SEP] prose [SEP] when did prose become important in turkish culture ? [SEP] the style of the current novelists can be traced back to the " young pens " ( genc kalemler ) journal in the ottoman period . [SEP] what was the journal about ? [SEP] young pens was published in selanik under omer seyfettin , ziya gokalp and ali canip yontem . [SEP] were there any other important journals ? [SEP] they covered the social and political concepts of their time with the nationalistic perspective . they were the core of a movement which became known as the " national literature . " [SEP] what kinds of concepts ?

[SEP] 1990 , the rohingya - led national democratic party for human rights won four seats in the burmese parliament . [SEP] were they successful ? [SEP] the burmese military junta banned the national democratic party for human rights in 1992 . its leaders were arrested , jailed and tortured . [SEP] calling for the recognition of the term " rohingya " , based on local indian names of arakan ( rohan and rohang ) , as the official ethnicity of arakanese indians . [SEP] the burmese military junta banned the national democratic party for human rights in 1992 . its leaders were arrested , jailed and tortured . [SEP] what were some of their other goals and ideals ? [SEP] mahmud suggested that either rohingya - majority northern arakan remain under the central government or be made a separate province . [SEP] is that how the majority of people felt ? [SEP] however , during the burmese general election , 1960 , prime minister u nu 's pledges included making all of arakan into one province . [SEP] in march 1979 , the military budget was 6.4 million us$ , which was 8.3 percent of the government budget , but only 2.2 of gross national product . [SEP] what else is important to know about this ? [SEP] after the soviet intervention , the defence budget increased to 208 million us$ in 1980 , and 325 million us$ by 1981 . the untouchables ( 1959 tv series ) [SEP] series overview [SEP] what was the series about [SEP] the series originally focused on the efforts of a real - life squad of prohibition agents employed by the united states department of the treasury and led by eliot ness ( stack ) , [SEP] who were some of the other actors that starred in the series [SEP] neville brand as al capone , [SEP] were there others as well [SEP] an array of gangsters and villains of the 1930s , including ma barker , dutch schultz , bugs moran , vincent " mad dog " coll , legs diamond , lucky luciano , and in one episode , nazi agents . [SEP] chairman william s. paley rejected it on the advice of network vice president hubbell robinson . abc agreed to air the series , and the untouchables premiered on october 15 , 1959 . [SEP] to record the voices of the historical figures , voice actors were filmed and special effects were used to alter lip - syncing for the new dialogue . [SEP] the aircraft weighed about 2,710 lb ( 1,230 kg ) , and takeoff was hampered by a muddy , rain - soaked runway . [SEP] were there other challenges ? [SEP] the aircraft fought icing , flew blind through fog for several hours , and lindbergh navigated only by dead reckoning . ( [SEP] did lindbergh get there safely ? [SEP] ) he landed at le bourget aerodrome at 10:22 p.m. on saturday , may 21 . [SEP] what did he do after he landed ? [SEP] a crowd estimated at 150,000 stormed the field , dragged lindbergh out of the cockpit , and literally carried him around above their heads for " nearly half an hour " . [SEP] did he do any other notable flights ?

jerry west [SEP] college career [SEP] tell me some about his college career [SEP] west graduated from east bank high school in 1956 , and more than 60 universities showed interest in him . [SEP] which university did he go to ? [SEP] he eventually chose to stay in his home state and attend west virginia university ( wvu ) , located in morgantown . [SEP] did he start playing for them immediately ? [SEP] freshman year ( 1956 - 57 ) , west was a member of the wvu freshman squad that achieved a perfect record of 17 wins without a loss [SEP] what were his other achievements his first year ? [SEP] west scored 17.8 points per game and averaged 11.1 rebounds ; he also started in all 28 games while shooting 49.6 % from the field and 73.2 % from the free throw line . [SEP] did he get any wards or accolades that year ?
jerry west [SEP] college career [SEP] tell me some about his college career [SEP] west graduated from east bank high school in 1956 , and more than 60 universities showed interest in him . [SEP] freshman year ( 1956 - 57 ) , west was a member of the wvu freshman squad that achieved a perfect record of 17 wins without a loss [SEP] what were his other achievements his first year ? [SEP] what did he do as president of the association ? [SEP] as president , he appeared before congress to speak about baseball 's reserve clause . [SEP] what other things was he doing ?
bob feller [SEP] later life [SEP] what was he doing in his later life ? [SEP] feller was elected the inaugural president of the major league baseball players ' association in 1956 . [SEP] what did he do as president of the association ? [SEP] as president , he appeared before congress to speak about baseball 's reserve clause . [SEP] what other things was he doing ? [SEP] feller was the first player to get a franchise to agree to a share of game receipts when he was the starting pitcher for indians ' games . [SEP] was the the first to do anything else ?
bob feller [SEP] later life [SEP] what was he doing in his later life ? [SEP] feller was elected the inaugural president of the major league baseball players ' association in 1956 . [SEP] what did he do as president of the association ? [SEP] as president , he appeared before congress to speak about baseball 's reserve clause . [SEP] what other things was he doing ? [SEP] feller was the first player to get a franchise to agree to a share of game receipts when he was the starting pitcher for indians ' games . [SEP] was the the first to do anything else ? [SEP] he was also the earliest player to incorporate himself ( as ro - fel , inc. ) . [SEP] did he have other firsts ?
bob feller [SEP] later life [SEP] what was he doing in his later life ? [SEP] feller was elected the inaugural president of the major league baseball players ' association in 1956 . [SEP] what did he do as president of the association ? [SEP] as president , he appeared before congress to speak about baseball 's reserve clause . [SEP] what other things was he doing ? [SEP] feller was the first player to get a franchise to agree to a share of game receipts when he was the starting pitcher for indians ' games . [SEP] was the the first to do anything else ? [SEP] he was also the earliest player to incorporate himself ( as ro - fel , inc. ) . [SEP] did he have other firsts ? [SEP] he was also one of the first players to work for the right of a player to enter free agency . [SEP] what other things were going on in his later life ?

[SEP] hbcu bands utilize the traditional " ankle - knee " high step and music selections are largely based on r&b , hip - hop , and contemporary popular music . [SEP] what else did they utilize in band ? [SEP] in addition to traditional drill formations , hbcu bands feature heavily choreographed dance routines as part of their performances . marching band [SEP] high step [SEP] what is high step ? [SEP] hbcu bands utilize the traditional " ankle - knee " high step and music selections are largely based on r&b , hip - hop , and contemporary popular music . [SEP] what else did they utilize in band ? [SEP] in addition to traditional drill formations , hbcu bands feature heavily choreographed dance routines as part of their performances . [SEP] what are some other traditional drill formations ? [SEP] many of these bands may have a twirler line and/or a dancer line , but not necessarily flag twirlers . [SEP] what else does the line consist of in the band ?

texas ( band ) [SEP] 1999 - 2001 : the hush and the greatest hits [SEP] what is " hush " ? [SEP] the band 's fifth album , the hush , was released in may 1999 and charted at no . 1 on the uk album charts in its first week of release . [SEP] what was a song from this album ? [SEP] a second single , " summer son " , was released in august 1999 , reaching no . 5 , the band 's seventh uk top 10 single at that point . [SEP] what was the first single ? [SEP] " in our lifetime " peaked at no . 4 on the uk singles charts and was also included on the notting hill film soundtrack that year . [SEP] where there any more singles from the album ? [SEP] a third and final single , " when we are together " , was released in november 1999 and narrowly missed the uk top 10 ( peaking at 12 ) . [SEP] so was the album a success then ?

[SEP] the band 's fifth album , the hush , was released in may 1999 and charted at no . 1 on the uk album charts in its first week of release . [SEP] what was a song from this album ? [SEP] " in our lifetime " peaked at no . 4 on the uk singles charts and was also included on the notting hill film soundtrack that year . [SEP] where there any more singles from the album ? [SEP] a third and final single , " when we are together " , was released in november 1999 and narrowly missed the uk top 10 ( peaking at 12 ) . [SEP] so was the album a success then ? [SEP] the album was certified 3 x platinum by the bpi for uk sales in excess of 900,000 copies . [SEP] did they have a greatest hits album ?

[SEP] public radio comedy / music program le show . the program is a hodgepodge of satirical news commentary , music , and sketch comedy that takes aim at the " mega morons of the mighty media " . [SEP] where does le show broadcast ? [SEP] national public radio and other public radio stations throughout the united states . since the merger of sirius and xm satellite radio services the program is no longer available on either . wayne n. aspinall [SEP] colorado river storage act of 1956 [SEP] what was the colorado river storage act of 1956 ? [SEP] the bill , sponsored by wayne aspinall and several western allies , called for damming several areas in the upper basin of the colorado river . [SEP] was the bill easy to pass ?
wayne n. aspinall [SEP] colorado river storage act of 1956 [SEP] what was the colorado river storage act of 1956 ? [SEP] the bill , sponsored by wayne aspinall and several western allies , called for damming several areas in the upper basin of the colorado river . [SEP] was the bill easy to pass ? [SEP] because of increased environmental awareness around the country , the majority of the public opposed the project . [SEP] was aspinall eventually able to get the bill to pass through congress ?
wayne n. aspinall [SEP] colorado river storage act of 1956 [SEP] what was the colorado river storage act of 1956 ? [SEP] the bill , sponsored by wayne aspinall and several western allies , called for damming several areas in the upper basin of the colorado river . [SEP] was the bill easy to pass ? [SEP] because of increased environmental awareness around the country , the majority of the public opposed the project . [SEP] was aspinall eventually able to get the bill to pass through congress ? [SEP] the bill passed the house 256 - 136 in march 1956 and then - president dwight eisenhower signed it into law soon thereafter . [SEP] what was aspinall political position during this time period ?
wayne n. aspinall [SEP] colorado river storage act of 1956 [SEP] what was the colorado river storage act of 1956 ? [SEP] the bill , sponsored by wayne aspinall and several western allies , called for damming several areas in the upper basin of the colorado river . [SEP] was the bill easy to pass ? [SEP] because of increased environmental awareness around the country , the majority of the public opposed the project . [SEP] was aspinall eventually able to get the bill to pass through congress ? [SEP] the bill passed the house 256 - 136 in march 1956 and then - president dwight eisenhower signed it into law soon thereafter . [SEP] what was aspinall political position during this time period ? [SEP] aspinall gained five other reclamation projects and three hydroelectric dams for the fourth district . [SEP] why did the people oppose the act ?
wayne n. aspinall [SEP] colorado river storage act of 1956 [SEP] what was the colorado river storage act of 1956 ? [SEP] the bill , sponsored by wayne aspinall and several western allies , called for damming several areas in the upper basin of the colorado river . [SEP] was the bill easy to pass ? [SEP] because of increased environmental awareness around the country , the majority of the public opposed the project . [SEP] was aspinall eventually able to get the bill to pass through congress ? [SEP] the bill passed the house 256 - 136 in march 1956 and then - president dwight eisenhower signed it into law soon thereafter . [SEP] what was aspinall political position during this time period ? [SEP] aspinall gained five other reclamation projects and three hydroelectric dams for the fourth district . [SEP] why did the people oppose the act ? [SEP] this became a volatile issue between environmentalists and water project advocates . [SEP] is there anything else significant about aspinall 's role in the colorado river storage act ?
wayne n. aspinall [SEP] colorado river storage act of 1956 [SEP] what was the colorado river storage act of 1956 ? [SEP] the bill , sponsored by wayne aspinall and several western allies , called for damming several areas in the upper basin of the colorado river . [SEP] was the bill easy to pass ? [SEP] because of increased environmental awareness around the country , the majority of the public opposed the project . [SEP] was aspinall eventually able to get the bill to pass through congress ? [SEP] the bill passed the house 256 - 136 in march 1956 and then - president dwight eisenhower signed it into law soon thereafter . [SEP] what was aspinall political position during this time period ? [SEP] aspinall gained five other reclamation projects and three hydroelectric dams for the fourth district . [SEP] why did the people oppose the act ? [SEP] this became a volatile issue between environmentalists and water project advocates . [SEP] signed the treaty of versailles on behalf of australia - the first time australia had signed an international treaty . [SEP] what did the treaty entail ?

[SEP] in 1919 hughes , with former prime minister joseph cook , travelled to paris to attend the versailles peace conference . he remained away for 16 months , [SEP] what happened at the conference ? [SEP] signed the treaty of versailles on behalf of australia - the first time australia had signed an international treaty . [SEP] what did the treaty entail ? [SEP] demanded heavy reparations from germany , suggesting a staggering sum of ps24,000,000,000 of which australia would claim many millions to off - set its own war debt . hiawatha [SEP] hiawatha belt [SEP] what is the hiawatha belt ? [SEP] the hiawatha belt is made of 6,574 wampum beads - 38 rows by 173 columns and has 892 white and 5,682 purple beads . [SEP] what does it represent ?
hiawatha [SEP] hiawatha belt [SEP] what is the hiawatha belt ? [SEP] the hiawatha belt is made of 6,574 wampum beads - 38 rows by 173 columns and has 892 white and 5,682 purple beads . [SEP] what does it represent ? [SEP] the purple represents the sky or universe that surrounds us , while the white represents purity and good mind ( good thoughts , forgiveness and understanding ) . [SEP] how are these made ?
hiawatha [SEP] hiawatha belt [SEP] what is the hiawatha belt ? [SEP] the hiawatha belt is made of 6,574 wampum beads - 38 rows by 173 columns and has 892 white and 5,682 purple beads . [SEP] what does it represent ? [SEP] the purple represents the sky or universe that surrounds us , while the white represents purity and good mind ( good thoughts , forgiveness and understanding ) . [SEP] how are these made ? [SEP] near its center , it contains a bead made of colonial lead glass . [SEP] are they made by hand ?

[SEP] during the early stages of the south african war 1899 - 1902 , the british army suffered defeats at the hands of the boer commandos , [SEP] what were the boer commandos ? [SEP] boer commandos , composed of men who were first - class shots and good horsemen . [SEP] who were the sharpshooters ?

[SEP] boer commandos , composed of men who were first - class shots and good horsemen . [SEP] who were the sharpshooters ? [SEP] volunteers who could both ride and shoot well . [SEP] what were the sharpshooters used for ? [SEP] the sharpshooters fought many small - scale actions against the boers , with increasing skill , and showed the value of mobile , well - armed and resourceful troops . [SEP] were there also non - sharpshooters that fought on the same side ? [SEP] i do n't know . [SEP] how were sharpshooters found or recruited ? [SEP] the government made a further call for yeomanry and between february and march , another 1,200 men were recruited by the sharpshooters committee . [SEP] in the early to mid-1990s , isaac , taylor and zac sang a cappella and recorded such classic songs as " rockin ' robin " , " splish splash " and " johnny b. goode " , [SEP] which other songs did they record ? [SEP] the band recorded two independent albums in their hometown of tulsa , boomerang ( recorded in autumn 1994 , released in 1995 ) and mmmbop ( released in 1996 ) . [SEP] did those two albums feature their a cappella singing ? [SEP] all three boys started their musical careers as pianists , but isaac eventually started playing guitar and zac started playing drums , while taylor continued as the keyboard player . [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] the boys then found themselves at the south by southwest ( aka sxsw ) music festival in austin , [SEP] did they perform at that festival ? [SEP] there , they were promptly signed by manager christopher sabec . he shopped them to several record companies , [SEP] which record company signed them ? [SEP] mercury . [SEP] did any other companies want to sign them ? [SEP] after this performance , they were signed almost immediately by mercury . [SEP] what did they release under the mercury label ? william lloyd garrison [SEP] organization and reaction [SEP] what kind of organization did garrison work with ? [SEP] in addition to publishing the liberator , garrison spearheaded the organization of a new movement to demand the total abolition of slavery in the united states . [SEP] who did garrison work with ? [SEP] january 1832 , he had attracted enough followers to organize the new - england anti - slavery society which , by the following summer , had dozens of affiliates and several thousand members . in december 1833 , [SEP] was he successful in his anti slavery work ? [SEP] founded the american anti - slavery society ( aas ) . although the new england society reorganized in 1835 as the massachusetts anti - slavery society , enabling state societies to form in the other new england states , [SEP] was garrison also an orator ( speaker ) ?

[SEP] in january 1946 , philip returned to the united kingdom on the whelp , and was posted as an instructor at hms royal arthur , the petty officers ' school in corsham , wiltshire . prince philip , duke of edinburgh [SEP] naval and wartime service [SEP] when did philip join the military ? [SEP] after leaving gordonstoun in 1939 , philip joined the royal navy , [SEP] did he serve in any war ? [SEP] during the second world war , he continued to serve in the british forces , [SEP] when did he retire from the forces ? [SEP] in january 1946 , philip returned to the united kingdom on the whelp , and was posted as an instructor at hms royal arthur , the petty officers ' school in corsham , wiltshire . [SEP] did philip go to college ? [SEP] graduating the next year from the royal naval college , dartmouth , as the best cadet in his course . [SEP] were there other wars that he was involved in ? [SEP] after the invasion of greece by italy in october 1940 , he was transferred from the indian ocean to the battleship hms valiant in the mediterranean fleet . [SEP] was he in the force with other royals ?

[SEP] in january 1946 , philip returned to the united kingdom on the whelp , and was posted as an instructor at hms royal arthur , the petty officers ' school in corsham , wiltshire . [SEP] after the invasion of greece by italy in october 1940 , he was transferred from the indian ocean to the battleship hms valiant in the mediterranean fleet . prince philip , duke of edinburgh [SEP] naval and wartime service [SEP] when did philip join the military ? [SEP] after leaving gordonstoun in 1939 , philip joined the royal navy , [SEP] did he serve in any war ? [SEP] during the second world war , he continued to serve in the british forces , [SEP] when did he retire from the forces ? [SEP] in january 1946 , philip returned to the united kingdom on the whelp , and was posted as an instructor at hms royal arthur , the petty officers ' school in corsham , wiltshire . [SEP] did philip go to college ? [SEP] graduating the next year from the royal naval college , dartmouth , as the best cadet in his course . [SEP] were there other wars that he was involved in ? palestinian art [SEP] politics [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] before 1948 , most palestinian artists were self - taught , painting landscapes and religious scenes in imitation of the european style . art exhibitions were almost unheard of . [SEP] what role does politics play in palestinian art ?
palestinian art [SEP] politics [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] before 1948 , most palestinian artists were self - taught , painting landscapes and religious scenes in imitation of the european style . art exhibitions were almost unheard of . [SEP] what role does politics play in palestinian art ? [SEP] while most of the art in his day explored religious themes and non - controversial issues , saig 's work ventured into politics . [SEP] what does saig 's work say about politics ?
palestinian art [SEP] politics [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] before 1948 , most palestinian artists were self - taught , painting landscapes and religious scenes in imitation of the european style . art exhibitions were almost unheard of . [SEP] what role does politics play in palestinian art ? [SEP] while most of the art in his day explored religious themes and non - controversial issues , saig 's work ventured into politics . [SEP] what does saig 's work say about politics ? [SEP] caliph umar at jerusalem gates c. 1920 , for example , seems to recount a popular religious legend about umar bloodlessly taking over jerusalem and ushering centuries of peace [SEP] what other political themes are present in palestinian artwork ?
palestinian art [SEP] politics [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] before 1948 , most palestinian artists were self - taught , painting landscapes and religious scenes in imitation of the european style . art exhibitions were almost unheard of . [SEP] what role does politics play in palestinian art ? [SEP] while most of the art in his day explored religious themes and non - controversial issues , saig 's work ventured into politics . [SEP] what does saig 's work say about politics ? [SEP] caliph umar at jerusalem gates c. 1920 , for example , seems to recount a popular religious legend about umar bloodlessly taking over jerusalem and ushering centuries of peace [SEP] what other political themes are present in palestinian artwork ? [SEP] many palestinians saw as divisive policies of the british during the mandate period which attempted to create friction between muslims and christian arabs . [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ?
palestinian art [SEP] politics [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] before 1948 , most palestinian artists were self - taught , painting landscapes and religious scenes in imitation of the european style . art exhibitions were almost unheard of . [SEP] what role does politics play in palestinian art ? [SEP] while most of the art in his day explored religious themes and non - controversial issues , saig 's work ventured into politics . [SEP] what does saig 's work say about politics ? [SEP] caliph umar at jerusalem gates c. 1920 , for example , seems to recount a popular religious legend about umar bloodlessly taking over jerusalem and ushering centuries of peace [SEP] what other political themes are present in palestinian artwork ? [SEP] many palestinians saw as divisive policies of the british during the mandate period which attempted to create friction between muslims and christian arabs . [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] after 1948 , ismail shammout , naji al - ali , mustafa al - hallaj , abdul hay mosallam and paul guiragossian tackled the painful memories of the nabka showing massacres , [SEP] how did these artists portray the massacres ?
